1. Overview 
Henav is a custom programming language designed and implemented as part of a Compiler Design 
course. The language draws from C in terms of variable naming conventions and expression syntax, 
but introduces a completely distinct set of keywords, control structures, and idioms. It supports five 
primitive data types, two different loop constructs, user-defined functions with typed parameters and 
return values, conditional branching, and basic I/O through print and scan statements. 
The Henav compiler is built using the Flex and Bison toolchain with all semantic logic and intermediate 
code generation (ICG) written in C. It implements all major front-end compilation phases: lexical 
analysis, syntax analysis, semantic checking, and ICG — producing both three-address code (TAC) 
and stack-machine instructions as output. Error detection is supported at all three phases with 
descriptive messages for lexical, syntactic, and semantic violations. 
2. Language Specification 
2.1 Data Types 
Henav is statically typed — every variable must be declared with an explicit type before use. Five 
primitive data types are supported: 
