2.4 Conditional Statements 
Henav replaces if / else-if / else with three dedicated, readable keywords. All conditions support any 
relational or logical expression. Only case_true is mandatory; the other two are optional: 
• case_true  a > b  { print a }                -- executes when condition is true (if) 
• case_false_if  a == b  { print "equal" }     
• case_false  { print b }                      -- chained condition (else-if) -- fallback block (else) 
2.5 Loops 
Two loop constructs cover the most common iteration patterns. The range loop iterates a variable from 
0 to n-1 with concise syntax: 
• loop(i to n) { ... }     -- i = 0, 1, 2, ..., n-1 
The conditional loop gives full C-style control with explicit initialization, condition, and increment: 
• conditional_loop(int i = 0; i < 10; i += 1) { ... } 
Inside any loop, stop exits immediately (like break) and skip jumps to the next iteration (like continue). 
Using either outside a loop triggers a semantic error. 
2.6 Functions 
Functions are declared outside the main body using the block keyword with a typed parameter list. 
They are called by name with a parenthesised argument list — literals and variables are both valid 
arguments: 
• block add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }   -- definition 
• add(5, 6);    or    add(x, y);              
2.7 Input / Output and Comments -- call 
• print "label: " + varname;   -- outputs a string and a variable value 
• scan varname;                
• !! This is a comment         -- reads a value from standard input -- single-line, fully ignored by the compiler 
3. Tools and Technologies 
The Henav compiler uses the standard Unix compiler-construction toolchain. Flex and Bison handle the 
declarative parts (tokenization and parsing) while C provides full control over semantic logic and code 
generation: 
