Flex and Bison were chosen because they are mature, industry-standard tools that produce efficient C 
code integrating cleanly with hand-written logic. Writing semantic analysis and ICG directly in C 
provided full control over critical data structures — particularly the symbol table, function table, and the 
label/loop context stacks used for nested control flow. 
4. Phases of Compiler Development 
Phase 1 — Lexical Analysis  (henav.l, Flex) 
The lexer is the first phase of the compiler, converting raw source text into a stream of typed tokens. It 
recognizes all Henav keywords (start, int, float, bool, block, loop, case_true, case_false_if, case_false, 
stop, skip, return, print, scan, to, conditional_loop), identifiers matching [a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*, integer 
and floating-point literals, double-quoted string literals, all arithmetic / relational / logical / assignment 
operators, and punctuation. Comments beginning with !! are discarded entirely. Whitespace and 
newlines are silently ignored. Any unmatched character triggers a 'Syntax Error: invalid token' message 
and returns the YYUNDEF token. 
Phase 2 — Syntax Analysis  (henav.y, Bison) 
The parser validates the token stream against the Henav BNF grammar using an LALR(1) algorithm 
generated by Bison. Grammar rules cover variable declarations and initializations, all expression forms 
with explicit operator precedence and associativity declarations, conditional statements, range and 
conditional loops, function definitions with typed parameter lists, return statements, and stop/skip within 
loop bodies. To correctly handle nested control flow, two stacks are maintained at runtime: a label 
context stack for nested if-blocks, and a loop label context stack for nested loops. Each stack saves the 
enclosing block's labels before entering an inner block and restores them on exit, ensuring correct 
branch targeting at any nesting depth. 
Phase 3 — Semantic Analysis 
Semantic checks are embedded as C code inside Bison grammar actions, running as each construct is 
recognized. A symbol table of up to 100 entries stores each variable's name, type (int/float/bool 
encoded as 0/1/2), initialization flag, current value (as a double to unify numeric types), and scope (0 = 
global, 1 = function-local). The following checks are enforced at compile time: 
• Undeclared variable — referencing a name not in the symbol table is a semantic error. 
• Uninitialized variable — reading a variable before it has been assigned a value is flagged. 
• Duplicate declaration — declaring the same name twice in the same scope is rejected. 
• Division by zero — a literal zero divisor in / or % expressions triggers an immediate error. 
• stop / skip outside a loop — the in_loop flag is checked; misuse produces a clear error 
message. 
• Scope cleanup — on function exit, all local variables (scope = 1) are removed from the table. 
Phase 4 — Intermediate Code Generation (ICG) 
The compiler produces two parallel forms of intermediate code from a single pass. Three-Address 
Code (TAC) uses auto-generated temporaries (t1, t2, t3, ...) to hold subexpression results, emitting 
instructions such as t1 = a + b, if t2 > 0 goto L1, and L1: label. Simultaneously, stack-machine 
instructions are emitted: PUSH for constants, LOAD for variables, STORE for assignments, arithmetic 
opcodes (ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, MOD), comparison opcodes (GT, LT, EQ, GTE, LTE, NE), logical 
opcodes (AND, OR, NOT), conditional jumps (JIF, GOTO), and function-call instructions (CALL, 
RETURN). A constant folding optimization is also applied: when both operands of an arithmetic 
expression are compile-time constants, the result is computed immediately and emitted directly rather 
than generating a temporary and an operation. 
Phase 5 — Function Handling 
Functions require special treatment in a single-pass design. At definition time, the parser stores each 
function's name, parameter names and types, complete body instruction sequence, and return 
expression in a function table (up to 100 entries, each supporting up to 20 parameters). At call time, the 
compiler looks up the function, binds the caller's argument values to parameter names by position, 
replays the stored body instructions with parameter substitution applied, and evaluates the return 
expression with the bound values to compute the result. This approach delivers correct function call 
semantics — including parameterized calls and return values — without requiring a second pass over 
the source. 
5. Error Detection and Reporting 
Henav detects and reports errors at all three front-end phases, giving the programmer precise 
diagnostic information: 
Phase 
Error Handling Approach 
Lexical 
Unmatched characters print 'Syntax Error: invalid token <char>' 
and return YYUNDEF, propagating as a syntax error to the parser. 
Syntax 
Bison calls yyerror(), printing 'Syntax Error: <message>' and 
setting the global syntax_error flag. Parsing continues for further 
diagnostics. 
Semantic 
Grammar actions print specific messages — e.g. 'Semantic Error: 
x undeclared', 'Semantic Error: Div by zero', 'Semantic Error: stop 
used outside loop' — and set the semantic_error flag. 
6. Key Design Decisions & Conclusion 
Key Design Decisions 
• Custom keywords (case_true, block, loop, stop, skip) give Henav a distinct identity while 
keeping structural logic familiar to anyone with C experience. 
• bool literals true/false map to '1'/'0' strings in the lexer, letting booleans participate in arithmetic 
without a separate evaluation code path. 
• Two loop constructs — a concise range loop for 0-to-n counting and a full conditional loop for 
general iteration — cover the vast majority of real use cases with clean syntax. 
• Label context stacks (for if-blocks) and loop label context stacks correctly save and restore 
branch targets across arbitrarily nested control structures, supporting deep nesting. 
• Dual ICG output (TAC + stack instructions) demonstrates two complementary intermediate 
representations produced in a single compiler pass, enriching the project as a learning exercise. 
• A dual-scope symbol table (global = 0, local = 1) encoded as a simple integer field keeps scope 
management lightweight and correct without complex data structures. 
Conclusion 
The Henav compiler is a complete, working implementation of a compiler front-end covering all five 
major phases: lexical analysis, syntax analysis, semantic checking, intermediate code generation, and 
function handling. Every core language feature — typed variables, four operator categories, conditional 
branching, two loop forms, functions with typed parameters and return values, I/O, and comments — is 
fully implemented and semantically validated. 
Built entirely with Flex, Bison, and C, the project translates textbook compiler theory directly into a 
functional, testable program. The deliberate design choices — unique keywords, readable conditional 
syntax, dual loop constructs, dual ICG output — make Henav a cohesive and self-consistent language 
rather than a stripped-down C imitation. The Henav compiler successfully demonstrates, end to end, all 
